04435nam a22005655i 9780822398073DE-B159720210106113355.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||210106t19951995ncu    fo  d z      eng d  a97808223980737 a10.1515/97808223980732doi  a(DE-B1597)553202  a(OCoLC)1229161526  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  ancucUS-NC 7aPER0040302bisacsh1 aHalberstam, Jack, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aSkin Shows :bGothic Horror and the Technology of Monsters /cJack Halberstam. 1aDurham : bDuke University Press, c[1995] 4cÂ©1995  a1 online resource (232 p.) :b6 b&w photographs  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tAcknowledgments -- t1 Parasites and Perverts: An Introduction to Gothic Monstrosity -- t2 Making Monsters: Mary Shelley's Frankenstein -- t3 Gothic Surface, Gothic Depth: The Subject of Secrecy in Stevenson and Wilde -- t4 Technologies of Monstrosity: Bram Stoker's Dracula -- t5 Reading Counterclockwise: Paranoid Gothic or Gothic Paranoia? -- t6 Bodies That Splatter: Queers and Chain Saws -- t7 Skinflick: Posthuman Gender in Jonathan Demme's The Silence of the Lambs -- t8 Conclusion: Serial Killing -- tNotes -- tBibliography -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aIn this examination of the monster as cultural object, Judith Halberstam offers a rereading of the monstrous that revises our view of the Gothic. Moving from the nineteenth century and the works of Shelley, Stevenson, Stoker, and Wilde to contemporary horror film exemplified by such movies as Silence of the Lambs, Texas Chainsaw Massacre, and Candyman, Skin Shows understands the Gothic as a versatile technology, a means of producing monsters that is constantly being rewritten by historically and culturally conditioned fears generated by a shared sense of otherness and difference.Deploying feminist and queer approaches to the monstrous body, Halberstam views the Gothic as a broad-based cultural phenomenon that supports and sustains the economic, social, and sexual hierarchies of the time. She resists familiar psychoanalytic critiques and cautions against any interpretive attempt to reduce the affective power of the monstrous to a single factor. The nineteenth-century monster is shown, for example, as configuring otherness as an amalgam of race, class, gender, and sexuality. Invoking Foucault, Halberstam describes the history of monsters in terms of its shifting relation to the body and its representations. As a result, her readings of familiar texts are radically new. She locates psychoanalysis itself within the gothic tradition and sees sexuality as a beast created in nineteenth century literature. Excessive interpretability, Halberstam argues, whether in film, literature, or in the culture at large, is the actual hallmark of monstrosity.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Jan 2021) 0aGothic revival (Literature)zGreat Britain. 0aHorror filmsxHistory and criticism. 0aHorror tales, EnglishxHistory and criticism. 0aLiterature and technologyzGreat Britain. 0aMonsters in literature. 0aMonsters in motion pictures. 7aPERFORMING ARTS / Film & Video / History & Criticism.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertDUK Archive eBook-Package 1964-1999z978311071360240uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9780822398073zCo-access DOI >> click Walter de Gruyter40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780822398073423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780822398073.jpg  a978-3-11-071360-2  DUK Archive eBook-Package 1964-1999c1964d1999  aEBA_DUK_ALL  aEBA_DUK_EALL  aEBA_DUK_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles